article.headline: Iowa State 77, Baylor 51
article.story: AMES, Iowa (AP) -- He dunked, he ran the floor, he rebounded and he even made a 3-pointer. Freshman Rahshon Clark was having the time of his life. Clark scored 15 of his season-high 19 points during a 19-0 run at the end of the first half, breaking the game open and leading Iowa State to a 77-51 victory over Baylor on Tuesday night. "I just went out there to have fun," Clark said. "I saw they weren't getting back, so I just ran." This was one time the entire Iowa State team had fun. Following up on their upset of No. 14 Oklahoma, the Cyclones (10-8, 2-5 Big 12) ran with impunity, shot 52.5 percent, forced 23 turnovers and sank five 3-pointers -- one more than they had made in the three previous games combined. With a two-game winning streak, Iowa State has consecutive victories for the first time since finishing December with four straight wins. "I think we did have some fun tonight and I think they did do some things together that they enjoyed," said Iowa State coach Wayne Morgan, whose team had lost six straight before this mini-surge. "Obviously, tonight was a lot more fun than some of the other games." It all stemmed from Clark's scoring outburst, which began when Iowa State was clinging to an 18-17 lead in what to that point had been a listless game. Clark topped his previous best of 14 points during the big run and made all seven of his shots -- a 3-pointer, three layups in transition, a dunk, a tip-in and a putback on Will Blalock's airball. "We got the whole spectrum tonight from him," Morgan said. "He did everything. He was really terrific. He works hard every day. He deserved to have a night like tonight and he really enjoyed it." Thanks mostly to Clark, Iowa State's lead quickly ballooned to 37-17. Baylor (9-9, 1-6) went the final 7:32 of the half without a field goal, getting only a solitary free throw from Tommy Swanson, and never recovered. The Cyclones would lead by as many as 33 in the second half. "The biggest thing was we didn't make shots, we turned the ball over and gave them some easy baskets," Baylor coach Scott Drew said. "With a young, inexperienced team, a lot of times when things go bad, they go bad, and that's what happened to us during that stretch." Curtis Stinson added 15 points, six assists and four steals for Iowa State. Freshman Tasheed Carr scored 11, while Jared Homan and Damion Staple had 10 each. Clark finished 9-for-13 from the field, made three steals and grabbed eight rebounds, seven on the offensive end. "He was a spark for their team," Baylor's Aaron Bruce said. "We didn't have someone tall enough and quick enough to guard him. You put a guard on him and he's too big and you put a big on him and he's too quick. He's a tough matchup for us." Baylor, which has only six scholarship players, has lost four straight and five of its last six after a promising start. Patrick Fields led Baylor with 16 points and was his team's only player in double figures. Bruce, coming off a 27-point outing against Texas A&M, scored only nine on 3-for-7 shooting. The 6-foot-3 freshman had been averaging 17.2. "It's the dog days of February," Drew said. "Everyone says this is a tough time of year. All season long we've been very competitive, been in most games all the way except for a couple of games. Tonight, for some reason, we just hit that drought." The Bears also caught Clark in high gear and had no answer. The birth of a star? "I hope so," Morgan said. "I think he's going to be an excellent player here. I think he's got the level of talent to be a star, but stars are measured over time."
